---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="visas · wanderlust"
  description="Visa notes for Indian passport holders, grouped by visa regime."
>
  <section class="mx-auto max-w-2xl">
    <h1 class="font-display text-4xl font-medium leading-[1.05] tracking-tight md:text-5xl">
      Visas for Indian passport.
    </h1>
  </section>

  <aside class="mx-auto mt-8 max-w-2xl border-l-2 pl-6 py-2" style="border-color: var(--color-accent)">
    <p class="font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest" style="color: var(--color-accent)">
      Disclaimer
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed">
      Visa rules change. Treat these as a starting point and verify on the
      official consulate site before you apply.
    </p>
  </aside>

  <nav class="mx-auto mt-8 max-w-2xl" aria-label="Visa sections">
    <p class="font-mono text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest" style="color: var(--color-muted)">Jump to</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 flex flex-wrap gap-x-5 gap-y-2">
      {[
        ['schengen', 'Schengen'],
        ['egypt', 'Egypt'],
        ['sri-lanka-eta', 'Sri Lanka'],
        ['thailand', 'Thailand'],
        ['vietnam', 'Vietnam'],
        ['indonesia', 'Indonesia'],
        ['japan', 'Japan'],
        ['usa', 'USA'],
      ].map(([id, label]) => (
        <li>
          <a
            href={`#${id}`}
            class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-widest hover:text-[color:var(--color-ink)]"
            style="color: var(--color-accent)"
          >
            {label}
          </a>
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  </nav>

  <div class="prose-trip mt-12">
    <h2 id="schengen">Schengen</h2>

    <p style="color: var(--color-muted)">
      From 3 of my own Schengen visa applications, 100% approval rate.
    </p>

    <p>
      One short-stay Schengen visa covers travel across all 29 member states.
      Apply through the consulate's visa partner (VFS Global, or BLS
      International for some countries such as Spain). Choose the country where
      you'll spend the most nights as the issuing consulate, or the country of
      first entry if the trip begins there or nights are split evenly.
    </p>

    <h3>Countries covered</h3>

    <p>
      Austria, Belgium, Bulgaria, Croatia, Czechia, Denmark, Estonia, Finland,
      France, Germany, Greece, Hungary, Iceland, Italy, Latvia, Liechtenstein,
      Lithuania, Luxembourg, Malta, Netherlands, Norway, Poland, Portugal,
      Romania, Slovakia, Slovenia, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland.
    </p>

    <h3>Documents</h3>

    <ul>
      <li>Valid passport, plus photocopies of the first and last pages</li>
      <li>Completed visa application form</li>
      <li>Passport-size photograph per Schengen specs (35x45mm, white background)</li>
      <li>Visa fee payment receipt</li>
      <li>Confirmed return flight tickets (Emirates and Finnair sell fully refundable fares, useful since approval isn't guaranteed)</li>
      <li>Internal travel across countries (trains, buses, intra-Schengen flights)</li>
      <li>Hotel bookings covering every night of the stay (Agoda and similar OTAs have refundable rooms)</li>
      <li>Travel insurance with 30,000 EUR medical coverage</li>
      <li>Cover letter with day-wise itinerary</li>
      <li>
        Financial proof (depends on your work situation)
        <ul>
          <li>If employed: NOC from your employer (mandatory), 3 months of payslips, ITR for the last 2 years, and your 6 months of bank statements</li>
          <li>If self-employed or running a business: business registration or GST certificate, ITR for the last 2 years, and 6 months of business and personal bank statements</li>
          <li>If not working (student, between jobs, retired, dependent): sponsorship letter, sponsor's financial proofs (as per their work situation above), and proof of your relationship to the sponsor</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Event tickets (Tomatina, Oktoberfest, a marathon) help anchor the
      "purpose of visit". Print them.
    </p>

    <h3>Cost</h3>

    <p>
      Budget around 15,000 INR all in: the Schengen visa fee plus the VFS or
      BLS appointment and service charges.
    </p>

    <p>
      A few Indian providers now sell visa-rejection insurance for around
      500 INR. Worth considering since the visa fee itself is non-refundable.
    </p>
    <h2 id="egypt">Egypt</h2>

    <p style="color: var(--color-muted)">
      Arrange a visa before you travel, either the embassy sticker visa or the online e-visa. A Sinai-only trip is the exception.
    </p>

    <p>
      The embassy route is what I did. Apply at the Egyptian embassy or consulate in India before travel. The main friction point is the travel agent letter - the embassy asks for a letter from a registered Egyptian travel agent as part of the application, and finding one willing to issue it took some effort. If you're planning this trip and want the contact I used, reach out.
    </p>

    <p>
      You can now skip the in-person hassle with an e-visa, applied online. It takes the same documents, the travel agent letter included, but you don't have to visit the embassy to submit them or collect your passport.
    </p>

    <h3>Documents</h3>

    <ul>
      <li>Valid passport</li>
      <li>Completed visa application form</li>
      <li>Passport-size photographs</li>
      <li>Confirmed return flight tickets</li>
      <li>Hotel bookings for the duration of stay</li>
      <li>Travel agent letter from an Egyptian travel agency (the key document - harder to get than it sounds)</li>
      <li>Bank statements</li>
      <li>Cover letter with itinerary</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Sinai-only exception</h3>

    <p>
      If you're only visiting the Sinai resorts (Sharm el-Sheikh, Dahab), you may be eligible for a visa exemption or visa on arrival. Check the official guidance for the current rules. Anything beyond Sinai (Cairo, Luxor, Aswan) needs a full visa.
    </p>

    <h3>Cost</h3>

    <p>
      It cost me around 5,000 INR all in: the visa fee plus the Egyptian agent's assistance for the letter.
    </p>

    <h2 id="sri-lanka-eta">Sri Lanka ETA</h2>

    <p>
      Indian passport holders need an ETA. Apply at <a href="https://www.eta.gov.lk" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">eta.gov.lk</a> before travel. The application takes a few minutes and approval is usually instant or within a few hours.
    </p>

    <h3>Notes</h3>

    <ul>
      <li>$20 USD for Indian nationals</li>
      <li>Apply online before departure, not on arrival</li>
      <li>Valid for 30 days, double entry</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="thailand">Thailand</h2>

    <p style="color: var(--color-muted)">
      The rules for Indian passport holders keep changing. Check the Royal Thai Embassy website for the latest before you book.
    </p>

    <p>
      Entry has swung between a visa, visa on arrival, and brief visa-free spells, so don't rely on what was true last year. Every time I've been, I've needed a visa, and the visa on arrival ran me around 2,000 THB. Whatever the current rule, carry a return flight ticket, hotel bookings, and some US dollars, since immigration can ask for proof of funds and onward travel at the airport.
    </p>

    <h2 id="vietnam">Vietnam (e-Visa)</h2>

    <p style="color: var(--color-muted)">
      Indian passport holders need a visa. The e-Visa is the simple route, apply online before you fly. Use only the official portal, evisa.gov.vn; lookalike sites charge extra.
    </p>

    <h3>Notes</h3>

    <ul>
      <li>USD 25 single entry, USD 50 multiple entry</li>
      <li>Valid for up to 90 days; choose single or multiple entry</li>
      <li>Apply online at evisa.gov.vn before departure, not on arrival</li>
      <li>Processing is usually around 3 working days (allow up to a week)</li>
      <li>Passport must be valid for at least 6 months from arrival</li>
      <li>Carry a printed copy of the approved e-Visa for immigration</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="indonesia">Indonesia (Visa on Arrival)</h2>

    <p style="color: var(--color-muted)">
      Indian passport holders get a Visa on Arrival (VOA) for Bali. Rules and fees change, so check the official Directorate General of Immigration site (molina.imigrasi.go.id) before you fly.
    </p>

    <p>
      I availed the VOA at Denpasar (DPS) on arrival. It's a paid, single-entry visa, so carry a return or onward ticket.
    </p>

    <h3>Notes</h3>

    <ul>
      <li>About 35 USD when I went; carry change to pay and confirm the current fee</li>
      <li>Valid for 30 days, extendable once for another 30 days</li>
      <li>Passport must be valid for at least 6 months from arrival</li>
      <li>Carry a return or onward ticket; immigration can ask for it</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="japan">Japan</h2>

    <p style="color: var(--color-muted)">
      Indian passport holders need a tourist visa before travel; there's no visa-free or visa-on-arrival entry. Apply ahead through the Japan visa application centre (VFS Global) or the embassy or consulate.
    </p>

    <p>
      It's a single-entry short-stay (tourist) visa. The visa fee itself is low, but the application centre adds its own service charge, so check the current total before you go. India is also covered by Japan's e-Visa, so for eligible applicants you can apply online instead of submitting in person; verify your eligibility and the current process on the official portal first.
    </p>

    <h3>Documents</h3>

    <ul>
      <li>Valid passport</li>
      <li>Completed visa application form</li>
      <li>Passport-size photograph per Japan specs (45x45mm, white background)</li>
      <li>Confirmed return flight tickets</li>
      <li>Hotel bookings for the duration of stay</li>
      <li>Day-wise itinerary</li>
      <li>Financial proof: recent bank statements and ITR; an employment or business letter helps</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="usa">USA (B1/B2)</h2>

    <p style="color: var(--color-muted)">
      There's no visa-free or visa-on-arrival option for Indian passport holders. You need a visa before you travel. The B1/B2 visitor visa covers both business (B1) and tourism (B2), and for Indian nationals it's typically issued for 10 years, multiple entry.
    </p>

    <p>
      The process is online-first, then in person. Fill the DS-160 form, pay the MRV visa fee (around $185, check the current amount), create a profile on the official appointment portal, and then book two appointments: a biometrics appointment at an Offsite Facilitation Centre (OFC) and the consular interview at the embassy or consulate. Some applicants qualify for an interview waiver (dropbox) on renewal; check your eligibility before booking the full interview.
    </p>

    <h3>Documents</h3>

    <ul>
      <li>Valid passport (plus any old passports with prior US visas)</li>
      <li>DS-160 confirmation page</li>
      <li>MRV fee payment receipt</li>
      <li>Appointment confirmation (OFC and interview)</li>
      <li>Passport-size photograph per US specs (51x51mm, white background)</li>
      <li>Supporting documents for the interview: proof of funds, employment or business proof, and ties to India (the interview is brief, but carry them)</li>
      <li>If the trip is company sponsored, a letter from your employer (and an invitation letter from the US host, if there is one)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Getting an interview slot</h3>

    <p>
      Interview wait times swing a lot by city and season, and slots can be scarce. Check current wait times on the official portal before you lock travel dates.
    </p>

    <p>
      Slots open in batches and get taken fast. Two things help:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>There are Telegram groups that notify you the moment new slots open up at a given consulate. Watching one of these and refreshing quickly is how a lot of people grab an earlier date.</li>
      <li>Agents can secure earlier slots for you, but they charge a hefty fee. Worth it only if your travel is fixed and you can't wait. You can reach out to me if you need contacts of trusted agents.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Cost</h3>

    <p>
      Budget the MRV fee (around $185) plus any service charges. The fee is non-refundable, so make sure the DS-160 is correct before you pay.
    </p>
  </div>
</Layout>
